      "post_content": "I actually think Wizards has pulled one over on the entire Magic community with hexproof. First they gave us shroud. Then [Troll Ascetic](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Troll Ascetic) was an amazing card. Then they gave us creatures like [Uril, the Miststalker](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Uril, the Miststalker) and [Thrun, the Last Troll](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Thrun, the Last Troll) just to show how amazing Hexproof could be (it wasn't called Hexproof yet, recall). Then, in the set that officially phased out Shroud, Innistrad, they show us just how abusable this \"fixed shroud\" could be with monstrosities like [Invisible Stalker](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Invisible Stalker) and [Geist of Saint Traft](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Geist of Saint Traft). Since those two, hexproof has been scaled back considerably to the point where the best hexproof creature in standard is most likely [Gladecover Scout](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Gladecover Scout). Benthy here is just another example of Wizards scaling back a mechanic that they probably knew would cause problems when they modified it from shroud, a \"balanced\" mechanic. ",
      "posted_by": "Avensai",
